avirus pandemic]], particularly the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United States]]. The legislation passed the House 415\u20132 on March 4 and the Senate 96\u20131 on March 5, 2020. The legislation received broad bipartisan support.\n\n==Proposal and negotiation process==\nOn February 24, 2020, the Trump administration asked Congress for $2.5 billion in emergency funding to combat the pandemic.<ref name=\"Fox News 2.5 billion emergency\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-administration-expected-congress-for-1b-to-combat-coronavirus |title=Trump administration asks Congress for $2.5B to combat coronavirus |last=O'Reilly |first=Andrew |last2=Pergram |first2=Chad |date=February 24, 2020 |website=[[Fox News]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226003550/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-administration-expected-congress-for-1b-to-combat-coronavirus |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Republican chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee, [[Richard Shelby]] of Alabama, criticized the $2.5 billion as a \"low ball\" request.<ref name=\"Politico bipartisan response\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/25/trump-officials-defend-coronavirus-request-117329 |title=Coronavirus triggers swift bipartisan backlash against Trump |last=Roubein |first=Rachel |last2=Ollstein |first2=Alice |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225235715/https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/25/trump-officials-defend-coronavirus-request-117329 |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"Lawmakers on both sides of the aisle were alarmed by what they deemed as the president\u2019s paltry request to fight the bug amid criticism that his administration has bungled its response and failed to keep the American people clued in about the potential severity of the outbreak.\"<ref name=\"Politico House 8.3 passage\" /> Shortly after the Trump administration requested the $2.5 billion, Senate Minority Leader [[Chuck Schumer]] unveiled a plan for \"$8.5 billion in emergency funding to combat the coronavirus.\"<ref name=\"The Hill Schumer 8.5\">{{Cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/484679-schumer-requesting-85-billion-in-emergency-funding-on-coronavirus |title=Schumer requesting $8.5 billion in emergency funding on coronavirus |last=Carney |first=Jordain |date=February 26, 2020 |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226153749/https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/484679-schumer-requesting-85-billion-in-emergency-funding-on-coronavirus |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the days leading up to the passage of the bill in the House and the Senate, negotiations had slowed down because of \"partisan disagreements on providing affordable access to treatment.\"<ref name=\"NPR Senate passage\" /> One of the main issues that caused disagreement and slow-down of the bill was vaccine affordability.<ref name=\"Politico House 8.3 passage\" />\n\nSeveral senators praised the process as cooperative and bipartisan. Senator [[Richard Shelby]], chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on Appropriations]], stated \"We worked together to craft an aggressive and comprehensive response that provides the resources the experts say they need to combat this crisis. I thank my colleagues for their cooperation and appreciate President Trump's eagerness to sign this legislation and get the funding out the door without delay.\"<ref name=\"NPR Senate passage\" /> Senate Majority Leader [[Mitch McConnell]] stated on March 4, 2020, of the bill that: \"The way to secure these urgently-needed resources with speed and certainty was to forgo partisan posturing, forgo micromanagement at the leadership level, and let bipartisan appropriators do their work.\"<ref name=\"NPR Senate passage\" />\n\nThe sponsor of the bill was representative [[Nita Lowey]] of New York, who chairs the House Appropriations Committee.<ref name=\"Bill summary\">{{cite web |title=H.R.6074 - Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act, 2020 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/6074 |website=Congress.gov |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR Senate passage\" />\n\n==Contents==\nThe bill includes $8.3 billion in emergency funding to combat the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref name=\"Bill summary\" /><ref name=\"NBC Senate 8.3 passage\" /> The $8.3 billion is divided into $7.8 billion in discretionary appropriations and $500 million in mandatory spending.<ref name=\"CBC Trump signs\">{{cite web |last1=Segers |first1=Grace |title=Trump signs $8.3 billion emergency package to combat coronavirus |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-signs-8-3-billion-emergency-package-to-combat-coronavirus/ |website=[[CBS News]] |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> The $500 million is for \"Medicare telehealth mandatory spending, which would allow Medicare providers to furnish telemedicine services to seniors.\"<ref name=\"CBC Trump signs\" />\n\nBroken down by category, the bill provides funding for the following purposes:\n*More than $3 billion for \"research and development of vaccines, as well as therapeutics and diagnostics\"\n*$2.2 billion \"in public health funding to aid in prevention, preparedness and response efforts \u2014 including $950 million to support state and local agencies\"\n*Almost $1 billion for \"medical supplies, health-care preparedness, Community Health Centers and medical surge capacity\"\n*$1.25 billion to fight COVID-19 internationally.<ref name=\"CNBC Senate passes 8.3\">{{cite web |last1=Breuninger |first1=Kevin |title=Senate passes $8.3 billion emergency coronavirus package, sending bill to Trump's desk |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/05/senate-passes-8point3-billion-coronavirus-bill-sending-it-to-trumps-desk.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBroken down organizationally, the bill provides emergency supplemental funding for the following departments and agencies with the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]]: \n*[[Food and Drug Administration]]\n*[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]\n*[[National Institutes of Health]]\n*Public Health and Social Services Emergency Fund.<ref name=\"Bill summary\" />\n\nOutside of HHS, the bill provides additional funding for: \n*[[Small Business Administration]]\n*[[Department of State]]\n*[[U.S. Agency for International Development]].<ref name=\"Bill summary\" />\n\n==Passage==\n[[File:President Trump Signs the Congressional Funding Bill for Coronavirus Response (49627907646).jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Trump, with Secretary of Health and Human Services [[Alex Azar]] signs the bill into law on March 6, 2020.]]\n\n===House===\nOn March 4, 2020, the bill passed the House on an overwhelming 415&ndash;2 vote.<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2020/roll086.xml Final Vote Results for Roll Call 86, QUESTION:  On Motion to Suspend the Rules and Pass; BILL TITLE: Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act, 2020], Office of the Clerk, United States House of Representatives.</ref><ref name=\"WSJ House Passes 8.3 billion\">{{cite web |last1=Duehren |first1=Andrew |title=House Passes $8.3 Billion Bill to Battle Coronavirus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/congress-reaches-8-billion-deal-to-combat-coronavirus-11583343193 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> Only two members, both Republicans, voted against the legislation: Representative [[Andy Biggs]] of Arizona and Representative [[Ken Buck]] of Colorado.<ref name=\"Politico House 8.3 passage\">{{cite web |last1=Emma |first1=Caitlin |last2=Scholtes |first2=Jennifer |title=House swiftly passes bipartisan $8.3B coronavirus package |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/04/house-coronavirus-funding-121065 |website=[[Politico]] |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn the House floor shortly before the vote on the bill, Democratic Representative Nita Lowey, the sponsor of the bill and the chairwoman of the [[House Appropriations Committee]], said, \"While we all ardently hope that this public health emergency does not worsen, House Democrats will not hesitate to act again if we must augment this funding with more resources.\"<ref name=\"Politico House 8.3 passage\" />\n\nDuring the vote on the measure in the House, Republican Representative [[Matt Gaetz]] of Florida wore a [[gas mask]] on the House floor.<ref name=\"CNN Gaetz gas mask\">{{cite web |last1=Kelly |first1=Caroline |title=Rep. Matt Gaetz wears gas mask on House floor during vote on coronavirus response package |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/04/politics/gaetz-coronavirus-gas-mask/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> Gaetz told journalists that \"members of congress are human petri dishes.\"<ref name=\"USA Today Gaetz gas mask\">{{cite web |last1=Behrmann |first1=Savannad |title=Rep. Matt Gaetz wore gas mask while House voted on coronavirus response bill |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/04/rep-matt-gaetz-wears-gas-mask-house-votes-coronavirus-bill/4956767002/ |website=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> Gaetz received criticism from Representative [[Bobby Rush]] for \"making light\" of the coronavirus pandemic,<ref name=\"WaPo Gaetz gas mask\">{{cite web |last1=Bellware |first1=Kim |title=Matt Gaetz made light of coronavirus by wearing a gas mask; a constituent just died of it |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/07/matt-gaetz-coronavirus-florida/ |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> and also from [[Walter Shaub]], the former director of the [[United States Office of Government Ethics]], who stated \"Matt Gaetz mocked fear over the coronavirus.\"<ref name=\"Time Gaetz criticism\">{{cite web |last1=Law |first1=Tara |title=Days After Rep. Matt Gaetz Wore a Gas Mask to Vote on COVID-19 Funding, the Virus Killed One of His Constituents |url=https://time.com/5799243/coronavirus-gas-mask-matt-gaetz-constituent/ |website=Time |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Senate===\nOn March 5, 2020, the bill passed the Senate by a 96\u20131 vote.<ref name=\"NBC Senate 8.3 passage\">{{cite web |last1=Shabad |first1=Rebecca |title=Senate passes $8.3 billion emergency bill to combat coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/senate-passes-8-3-billion-emergency-bill-combat-coronavirus-n1150521 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> Three senators&mdash;Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] of Vermont, Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] of Massachusetts, and Senator [[Mike Enzi]] of Wyoming&mdash;did not vote.<ref name=\"Senate passage summary\" /> Sanders was campaigning for the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2020 Democratic nomination for president]], while Warren ended [[Elizabeth Warren 2020 presidential campaign|her own campaign for the Democratic nomination]] the same day.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Herndon|first=Astead W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-drops-out.html|title= Elizabeth Warren, Once a Front-Runner, Drops Out of Presidential Race|date=March 5, 2020|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=March 5, 2020|last2=Goldmacher|first2=Shane|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe lone Senator to vote against the bill was [[Rand Paul]] of Kentucky.<ref name=\"Senate passage summary\">{{cite web |title=Roll Call Vote 116th Congress - 2nd Session |url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=116&session=2&vote=00066|publisher=United States Senate |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> Paul had proposed an amendment that would have offset some of the coronavirus funding with cuts to [[Bureau of Educational and Cultural Affairs|State Department Cultural Exchange programs]] and [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]].<ref name=\"NPR Senate passage\">{{cite web |last1=Grisales |first1=Claudia |title=Senate Approves Bipartisan Bill Providing Roughly $8 Billion For Coronavirus Response |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/04/812109864/bipartisan-negotiators-reach-deal-for-roughly-8-billion-for-coronavirus-response |website=[[NPR]] |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Courier Paul votes against\">{{cite web |last1=Tobin |first1=Ben |title=Kentucky Sen. Rand Paul votes against bill funding coronavirus emergency aid |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/kentucky-sen-rand-paul-votes-against-bill-funding-coronavirus-emergency-aid/ar-BB10NkCO |website=[[The Courier-Journal]] |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> Paul threatened to block the coronavirus legislation if his amendment did not receive a vote.<ref name=\"Courier Paul votes against\" /> The amendment failed on a 80\u201316 vote.<ref name=\"Courier Paul votes against\" />\n\n===President===\nOn March 6, 2020, President Trump signed the bill into law in the [[Diplomatic Reception Room (White House)|Diplomatic Reception Room]] at the [[White House]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Trump signs $8.3 billion emergency package to combat coronavirus |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-signs-8-3-billion-emergency-package-to-combat-coronavirus/ |website=CBS News |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC News nixed visit\">{{cite web |last1=Dareh |first1=Dareh |title=Trump, White House give differing explanations on briefly nixed CDC visit |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-white-house-give-differing-explanations-briefly-nixed-cdc-visit-n1151546 |website=NBC News |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> At the time of signing, President Trump stated \"So we\u2019re signing the $8.3 billion.  I asked for 2.5 and I got 8.3, and I\u2019ll take it\" and \"So here we are, $8.3 billion.  We\u2019re doing very well.  But it\u2019s an unforeseen problem.  What a problem.  Came out of nowhere, but we\u2019re taking care of it.\"<ref name=\"Prez Signing statement\">{{cite web |title=Remarks by President Trump at Signing of the Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act, 2020 |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-signing-coronavirus-preparedness-response-supplemental-appropriations-act-2020/ |website=WhiteHouse.gov |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident Trump signed the bill on the same day that global coronavirus cases surpassed 100,000.<ref name=\"CNBC Trump signs\">{{cite web |last1=Hirsch |first1=Lauren |last2=Kevin |first2=Breuninger |title=Trump signs $8.3 billion emergency coronavirus spending package |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/06/trump-signs-8point3-billion-emergency-coronavirus-spending-package.html |website=[[CNBC]] |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reaction==\nThe passage of the legislation was supported by the [[American Hospital Association]],<ref name=JointStmt>[https://www.aha.org/press-releases/2020-02-27-press-release-aha-ana-urge-congress-quickly-fund-health-care-readiness Press Release: AHA, ANA Urge Congress to Quickly Fund Health Care Readiness for Coronavirus], American Hospital Association/American Nurses Association (February 27, 2020).</ref> the [[American Nurses Association]],<ref name=JointStmt/> and the [[American Medical Association]].<ref>[https://www.ama-assn.org/press-center/ama-statements/ama-statement-congress-passing-supplemental-covid-19-appropriations AMA statement on Congress passing supplemental COVID-19 appropriations], American Medical Association (March 5, 2020).</ref>\n\nThe [[U.S. Chamber of Commerce]] supported the bill's inclusion of Economic Injury Disaster Loans (EIDLs) for small businesses affected by the coronavirus. EIDLs are a type of a \"structured low interest disaster loan program\" administered by the U.S. [[Small Business Administration]].<ref name=\"Chamber of Commerce letter\">{{cite web |last1=Bradley |first1=Neil |title=U.S. Chamber Letter on H.R. 6074, the \"Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act of 2020\" |url=https://www.uschamber.com/letters-congress/us-chamber-letter-hr-6074-the-coronavirus-preparedness-and-response-supplemental |website=U.S. Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Families First Coronavirus Response Act]]\n* [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act]]\n* [[List of bills in the 116th United States Congress]]\n* [[List of acts of the 116th United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/6074/text Full text of the law at Congress.gov]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Acts of the 116th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:United States federal emergency management legislation]]\n[[Category:United States federal health legislation]]\n[[Category:Law associated with the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States federal appropriations legislation]]\n", "name_user": "RobertskySemi", "label": "safe", "comment": "bypass redirect, replaced:act of Congressenacted on March 6, 2020. The legislation providedemergency supplemental appropriationsof $8.3 billion infiscal year 2020", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_Preparedness_and_Response_Supplemental_Appropriations_Act,_2020"}
